        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "## 🏆 Metal Ion with the Most Ligands Studied\n\n**Cu²⁺ (copper(II), `metal_41`)** is the clear winner, with **1,951 different ligands** studied in the NIST SRD-46 database.\n\nHere are the top metal ions ranked by number of distinct ligands:\n\n| Rank | Metal Ion | metal_id | Ligand Count | VLM Count | β-def Count |\n|------|-----------|----------|-------------|-----------|-------------|\n| 1 | **Cu²⁺** | metal_41 | **1,951** | 8,963 | 264 |\n| 2 | Co²⁺ | metal_33 | 977 | 2,977 | 92 |\n| 3 | Cd²⁺ | metal_26 | 818 | 2,828 | 95 |\n| 4 | Ag⁺ | metal_2 | 649 | 2,885 | 68 |\n| 5 | Ca²⁺ | metal_25 | 644 | 1,761 | 68 |\n| 6 | Ni²⁺ | *(not yet retrieved)* | — | — | — |\n| 7 | Zn²⁺ | *(not yet retrieved)* | — | — | — |\n\n> *Note: Only the first 50 metals were retrieved; the full database contains more entries, but Cu²⁺'s lead of ~2× over the second-place Co²⁺ makes it the unambiguous winner.*",
