      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### 🔬 Chemistry Insight\n\nCu²⁺'s dominance reflects its exceptional coordination chemistry versatility: it adopts square-planar, tetrahedral, and octahedral (Jahn-Teller distorted) geometries, and forms stable complexes with an enormous variety of donor atoms (N, O, S, P). This makes it a workhorse in bioinorganic chemistry (enzyme active sites, metalloproteins), analytical chemistry (chelation), and materials science. Its nearly **4,500 individual stability measurements** (VLMs) underscore decades of intense research interest.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes Database.*",
